  </introduction>

<section>
<title>Two <q>Ways of Thinking</q> About Integration: Summation vs. Antidifferentiation</title>
<introduction>

<p>
Beginning in <xref ref="Hist-intr"></xref> we observed that in our
study of Differential Calculus we it can helpful to change our
viewpoint from geometric (Leibniz), to the dynamic (Newton), and back
again, depending on the particular context.  Similarly the next
section describes two different, but equilvalent, ways to <q>think
about</q> integration. As before these two viewpoints are, more or
less, equivalent, but they provide different insights.
</p>
</introduction>
  <subsection  xml:id="SECTIONIntegrationAsASum">
    <title>Integration as  Summation</title>
    <p>
      In its simplest formulation, Differential Calculus  is about
       subtraction  <mdash/> differences. That is, given a function
      <m>y=y(x)</m>, when we differentiate it we find the
      infinitesimal difference <mdash/> which we've denoted as
      <m>\dx{y}</m> <mdash/> between two <q>infinitely close</q>
      points. Thus it seems reasonable to suppose that the reverse
      process is about addition <mdash/> summmation. 
    </p>
    <p>
      And indeed it is. <term>Integral Calculus</term>, in its simplest
      formulation, is the process of adding up all of the differentials of
      some unknown quantity in order to recover that quantity.
    </p>


    <!-- <p>  -->
    <!--   Notice we did not write <me>\int\dx{y} =y</me>.  This is -->
    <!--   because it is not (quite) true. There are an infinite number -->
    <!--   of possible values of <me>\int\dx{y}</me>. Fortunately, as we -->
    <!--   mentioned before, these all differ by constants.  Thus we can -->
    <!--   write something like <m>\int 2x\dx{x}=x^2+C</m> where <m>C</m> -->
    <!--   is an arbitrary constant.  This represents all of the possible -->
    <!--   functions whose derivative is <m>2x</m>, so with that in mind -->
    <!--   <m>\int 2x\dx{x}</m> is referred to as the indefinite integral -->
    <!--   or anti-derivative of <m>2x</m>.  These names come from the -->
    <!--   foundational switch from differentials to limits and -->
    <!--   derivatives, but we still want to emphasize that we integrate -->
    <!--   differentials, not functions (so the <m>\dx{x}</m> is not -->
    <!--   optional). -->
    <!-- </p> -->

    <p> 
      Suppose a point <m>P</m> on the real line begins at <m>P_0</m>
      and traces out a line segment of some unknown length,
      <m>x</m>.

    </p>

    <image source="IC/X0toX.png" width="35%">
      <shortdescription></shortdescription>
    </image>

<remark>
    <p>
      Notice that in this setting <m>x</m> represents the
      <em>length</em> of the line segment which <m>P</m> has traced
      out. In particular <m>x</m> is <em>not</em> the position
      (coordinate) of <m>P</m> on the line. It can't be because we have
      not specified an origin (zero) point.
    </p>
</remark>

    <p>
      In the sketch below we have partitioned the line segment between
      <m>P</m> and <m>P_0</m> (which we have re-labeled <m>x_n</m> and
      <m>x_0</m>) into subintervals. Note that <m>x_0</m>, <m>x_1</m>,
      <m>x_2 \ldots</m> represent positions on the line segment
      <m>x</m>. In particular, they do not represent lengths.
    </p>

    <figure  xml:id="FIGUREPartitionedInterval">
      <caption>A partitioned interval</caption>
      <image source="IC/FTC1.png" width="50%">
        <shortdescription></shortdescription>
      </image>
    </figure>

    <p>
      We represent the length of the  first subinterval of <m>x</m> with <m>\Delta
      x_1</m>, of the second with <m>\Delta x_2</m>, and so on.  In
      general  <m>\Delta{x_i}</m> represents the length of <m>i</m>th
      subinterval of <m>x</m>. Clearly the length of the line
      segment is
      <md>
        <mrow>\Delta{x_1}\amp{}+\Delta{x_2}+\Delta{x_3} +\cdots  +\Delta{x_{n-1}}+\Delta{x_n}</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp{} =  (x_1-x_0)+(x_2-x_1)+(x_3-x_2) +\cdots + (x_{n-1}-x_{n-2})+(x_n-x_{n-1})</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp{}=x_n-x_0</mrow>
<mrow>\amp{}=x</mrow>
      </md>.
      If the subintervals are all the same length, say
      <m>\Delta{x}</m>, then we no longer need the subscripts to
      distinguish them so we could write
      <me> \underbrace{\Delta{x}+\Delta{x} + \cdots{}+\Delta{x}}_{\text{n
      copies}}=x_n-x_0=x</me>
      
      instead.  But this is cumbersome and we are far too lazy to write
      all of that each time we want to indicate such a sum.  Leibniz proposed using 
      the letter <q>S</q> (first letter of the word <q>sum</q>) to
      simplify the summation  notation:


      <men xml:id="EQUATIONFinDiffSum">
        \int{}\Delta{x}=\underbrace{\Delta{x}+\Delta{x} + \cdots{}+\Delta{x}}_{\text{n
      copies}} = x_n-x_0 =x</men>
      and his notation has been universally adopted.
    </p> 

    <aside>
      <title>Historical Background</title>
      <p>
        Leibniz chose the letter <q>S</q> because
        it is the first letter of Latin word <foreign>summa</foreign>,
        from which we get the English word <q>sum.</q>
      </p>
      <p>
        To a modern eye the integral sign looks like a stylized
        letter <q>S,</q> and that is often how it is described. But
        it isn<rsq/>t stylized at all. In
        the seventeenth century a printed letter <q>S</q> typically
        had one of several forms, depending on where it appeared in a
        word.  One of these extended above and below the
        line of text, much as the modern form of the letter
        <q>f</q> extends above the line of text.  Leibniz adopted
        this doubly extended form of <q>S</q> as his summation
        sign. So the integral symbol isn<rsq/>t stylized at all.
         It is just  archaic.
      </p>
    </aside>

    <p> 
      We assume, with Leibniz, that <xref
      ref="EQUATIONFinDiffSum">equation</xref> remains true when the finite
      differences (<m>\Delta{x}</m>) are replaced with infinitesimal
      differences (<m>\dx{x}{}</m>): <men
      xml:id="EQUATIONDefInt2">\int{\dx{x} }=x_n-x_0=x</men>.
      The symbol 
      <q><m>\int </m></q> is called an 
      <term>integral sign</term>, and any expression starting with 
      <q><m>\int </m> </q> and ending with 
      <q><m>\dx{x} </m></q> is called an 
      <term>integral</term>. <xref ref="EQUATIONDefInt2">equation</xref> is the simplest possible integral.
    </p>


    <p>
      <xref ref="EQUATIONDefInt2">Equation</xref> says that if we add
      up the lengths of all of the differentials that make up the
      line segment from <m>x_0</m> to <m>x_n</m> we will get its
      length, <m>x_n-x_0</m>, which we have called <m>x</m>. 
    </p>
    <p>
      This is surely not surprising to you and you are probably
      wondering why we've taken the trouble to wrap such an obvious
      statement in this arcane notation. The reason is this: <xref
      ref="EQUATIONDefInt2">equation</xref> is a very simple form
      of what is known as the Fundamental Theorem of Calculus and we
      will need to become very comfortable with it. Later, when
      things get complex, it will be helpful to refer back to <xref
      ref="EQUATIONDefInt2">equation</xref> and remind ourselves
      that, at its heart, integration is about adding up differentials.
    </p>

    <paragraphs  xml:id="PARAGRAPHCoordinatesAndVariables">
      <title>DIGRESSION: Coordinates and  Variable Names</title>
      <p>
        <!-- You may also be wondering why we are being so punctilious about -->
        <!-- distinguishing the label of a point <m>P</m>, and its coordinate -->
        <!-- <m>x_n</m>.  -->
        In <xref ref="FIGUREPartitionedInterval"></xref> we were
        rather careless about the distinction between the label of a
        point, e.g.  <m>P</m> or <m>P_0</m>, and its coordinate,
        e.g. <m>x_1</m> or <m>x_2</m>. A natural question would be
        <q>Aren<rsq/>t they the same thing?</q>
      </p>
      <p> No, actually they aren<rsq/>t. The label of a point is the
      name we use to distinguish it from other points. The
      (horizontal) coordinate of a point is it<rsq/>s (horizontal)
      distance from the origin.  Consider the following diagram.<!--
      Suppose <m>P</m> is a point on -->
      <!-- the <m>x</m>-axis located at a distance of <m>x</m> to the right of -->
      <!-- the origin. Does <m>x</m> represent a length? If so, what is <m>x</m> -->
      <!-- the length of? -->
      </p>
      <image source="IC/VarX2.png" width="60%">
        <shortdescription></shortdescription>
      </image>
      <p>
        The labels (names) of the two points are <m>P_0</m> and <m>P</m>. Since
        <m>x_0</m> measures the distance between zero and <m>P_0</m> it is by
        definition the coordinate of the point labeled <m>P_0</m>. (If a vertical axis were
        present <m>x_0</m> would be the first coordinate and zero would be the
        second.) Similarly <m>x_n</m> is the coordinate of <m>P</m>.
      </p>
      <p>
        On the
        other hand since <m>x</m> <mdash/> the distance between <m>P_0</m> and
        <m>P</m> <mdash/> is not measured from the origin it is
        neither a coordinate nor the label of a point. 
        <!-- <p> -->
        <!-- Do you see -->
        <!-- what<rsq/>s going on here? The cooordinate <m>x</m> is indeed the length of the line segment between the origin and <m>P</m>. By definition every coordinate is the length of a line segment. But not every length  is necessarily a cooordinate. To see why consider the following sketch.  -->
        <!-- </p> -->
        <!-- <image source="IC/VarX2.png" width="60%"> -->
        <!-- <shortdescription></shortdescription> -->
        <!-- </image> -->
        <!-- <p> -->
        <!-- In this case <m>P</m> and <m>P_0</m> are the labels of the two points, -->
        <!-- whereas <m>x_n</m> and <m>x_0</m> are their coordinates, respectively. -->
        <!-- </p> -->
        It is the length of the line segment
        <m>\overline{P_0P}</m>. If we partition this line segment and
        compute <m>\int\dx{x} </m> we get 
        <me>\int\dx{x}=x_n-x_0=x</me> 
        which is equivalent to <xref
        ref="EQUATIONFTCSimple">equation</xref>.
      </p>
      <p>
        Since coordinates distinguish one point from another as well as
        their labels do,   a (very) common practice is to dispense with the
        labels altogether and make the coordinates serve both purposes as in
        the diagram below.
      </p>
      <image source="IC/VarX3.png" width="60%">
        <shortdescription></shortdescription>
      </image>
      <p>
        Strictly speaking this is an abuse of our notation and it can cause
        confusion because it isn<rsq/>t always clear whether <m>x_0</m> and
        <m>x_n</m> refer to points on the line, or their distance from the
        origin (their coordinates). Always be sure it is clear to you which
        usage is intended.
      </p>

      <p><alert>END OF DIGRESSION</alert></p>
    </paragraphs>
  </subsection>

  <subsection  xml:id="SECTIONIntAsAntiDiff">
    <title>Integration as Antidifferentiation</title>

    <definition  xml:id="DEFINITIONAntiderivative">
      <title>Antiderivative</title>

      <statement>
        <p>
          Suppose we have a function <men
          xml:id="EQUATIONDefAntideriv">y=F(t)</men> with derivative
          <m>\dfdx{y}{t}=F^\prime(t)=f(t)</m>. Then <m>F(t)</m> is
          called an <term>antiderivative</term> of <m>f(t)</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>
    <p>
      It follows immediately that if a function has one antiderivative
      then it has infinitely many since, by the Constant Rule, adding
      a constant to a function will not change its derivative. Thus if
      we know  one antiderivative of <m>f(x)</m>,
      then we know all (infinitely many) of the antiderivatives of
      <m>f(x)</m>. That is, if <m>F(x)</m> is an antiderivative of
      <m>f(x)</m> then so is <m>F(x)+5</m>. And <m>F(x)+80</m>. In
      fact if <m>C</m> ia a constant then so is <m>F(x)+C</m> for
      every possible value of <m>C</m>
because we get a (slightly) different antiderivative
      each time we add a constant to <m>F(x)</m>.  

Remember this. We
      will return to it when we discuss <xref ref="THEOREMFTC">equation</xref> below.
    </p>
    <p>
      Returning to <xref ref="EQUATIONDefAntideriv">equation</xref>, we
      know from our study of Differential Calculus that
      
      <me>\dx{y}=F^\prime(t)\dx{t}=f(t)\dx{t},</me>

      and we know from our work in
      <xref ref="SECTIONIntegrationAsASum"></xref> that
      
      <me>y=\int\dx{y}</me>.

      Therefore

      <me>y=\int\dx{y}= \int f(t)\dx{t}.</me>
    </p>
<aside>
<title>Comment</title>
<p>
      Observe that since <m>\dx{y} </m> is a differential it follows
      that <m>f(t)\dx{t}</m> is also a differential so the expression
      <m>\int f(t)\dx{t}</m> is a valid integral.

</p>
</aside>



    <p>
      Thus it appears that if <m>\dx{y}=f(t)\dx{t} </m> is known then
      <m>y=F(t)</m>, will be the antiderivative of <m>f(t)</m>. That is to
      say, integration appears to be <q>differentiation run backwards.</q>
    </p>

    <paragraphs xml:id="PARAGRAPHSDiffNotFunc"> 
      <title>We Integrate Differentials, Not Functions</title>
    <p>
      Integration can be usefully thought of as either summation or
      antidifferentiation. We will flip between these two mindsets as
      convenient in much the same way that we flipped between the
      dynamic (Newtonian) and geometric (Leibnizian) viewpoints in
      <xref ref="DiffCalcFromPractice"></xref>.
</p>
<p>
 But the integral sign is designed to
      indicate the summation of differentials, not
      antidifferentiation.  It is thus very easy to use the notation
      improperly. Sooner or later most people will fall into the
      habit of dropping the final <q><m>\dx{t}</m>,</q> writing
      <m>\int f(t)</m> instead of <m>\int f(t)\dx{t}</m>,
      and calling them both the integral of the function
      <m>f(t)</m>. This is an unfortunate, but common, abuse of the
      notation.  You can not integrate a function, only a
      differential. We <em>strongly</em> suggest that you take care to
      avoid this bad habit for as long as you can because it can be
      very confusing. Especially when the concepts are new.
    </p>
    <aside>
      <title>Mathematical Notation</title>
      <p>
        By calling <m>\int f(t)</m> meaningless we have overstated the
        situation a bit. If you study mathematics long enough you will
        encounter situations where <m>\int{f(t)}</m> is a perfectly reasonable notation to
        use. But we will not encounter them here, and it is best if you
        don<rsq/>t fall into this habit while you are still learning the
        basics.
      </p>
    </aside>

    <p>
      Remember that <me>\int f(t)</me> is meaningless no matter how
      convenient it might be because it indicates that we are summing
      a function, not a differential.
    </p>


    <p>
      But the meaning of <me>\int
      f(t)\dx{t}</me> is clear. We're summing up all of the
      differentials of the form <m>f(t)\dx{t} </m>.
    </p>

    <!-- <p> -->
    <!--   Suppose that <m>y=t^2</m> then <m>\dx{y} =2t\dx{t}</m>. Then -->
    <!--   <m>\int 2t\dx{t}</m> makes sense because the product -->
    <!--   <m>2t\dx{t}=\dx{y}</m> is a differential. But <m>\int 2t</m> -->
    <!--   is nonsense because <m>2t</m> alone is not a differential. -->
    <!-- </p> -->
    <!-- <p> -->
    <!--   In particular, <m>\int 2t</m> is meaningless. However  if <m>y=t^2</m> -->
    <!--   then what is probably meant is -->
    <!--   <men  xml:id="EQUATIONPlusCMissing">\int 2t\dx{t} = \int \dx{y}</men> which is equal to <m>y</m> since <m>\int \dx{y}</m> means  -->
    <!--   <q>add up the differentials of <m>y</m>.</q> -->
    <!-- </p> -->
    </paragraphs>
    <!-- <p> -->
    <!--   But remember that the title of this -->
    <!--   chapter is <q>Integration in its <em>Simplest</em> Form.</q> Running -->
    <!--   differentiation backwards is not as straightforward as it first -->
    <!--   appears to be. -->
    <!-- </p> -->


    <example xml:id="EXAMPLESimpleInt1">
      <title>A Simple Integration</title>
      <p>
        For example, can you find a formula for this integral?
        <me>\int2t\dx{t}</me>
      </p>
      <p>
        In this example clearly, <m>f(t)=2t</m>. Thus from <xref
        ref="DEFINITIONAntiderivative"></xref> we see that <m>F(t) =
        \frac{t^2}{2}</m> is one antiderivative, and we can capture all of the
        antiderivatives by adding an arbitrary constant, traditionally denoted
        <q><m>C</m>,</q> (presumably for <q>constant</q>) so we write
        <me>\int 2t\dx{t} = \frac{t^2}{2} + C.</me>
      </p>
      <p>
        As this example shows the expression <m>\int f(t)\dx{t} </m>
        represents a multifunction much like the <q> <m>\text{arc}</m></q>
        functions we encountered in <xref
        ref="CHAPTERcalc-trig"></xref>.
      </p>
      <p>
        None of the complicated domain and range difficulties that
        caused so many headaches with the inverse trigonometric
        functions will be in play here. Since these multifunctions are
        so simple, we will dispense with the formal language and call
        <m>F(t) = \frac{t^2}{2}+C</m> the <term>most general
        antiderivative</term> of <m>f(t) = t^2</m>. But remember that
        it is really a multfunction since <q><m>C</m></q> is
        unspecified.  There will be times when we will want to choose
        only one of the functions represented by <m>\int
        f(t)\dx{t}</m>. This will consist entirely of choosing the
        value of <m>C</m> that works for our problem.
      </p>
    </example>

    <p>
Since the early twentieth century integration theory has grown considerably beyond
      what we will be learning in this course. But the underlying
      notions of the integral as a sum and the integral as an
      antiderivative are still very helpful and we will rely on them
      rather heavily, at least at first.
    </p>

    <problem  xml:id="PROBLEMAntiDiffPractice">
      <p>
        Use your knowledge of Differentials Calculus to find the most
        general antiderivative.
        <ol cols="2" marker="i">
          <li>
            <m>\int t^2\dx{t}</m>
          </li>
          <li>
            <m>\int 3t-2\dx{t}</m>
          </li>
          <li>
            <m>\int 7\dx{t}</m>
          </li>
          <li>
            <m>\int \sin(t)\dx{t}</m>
          </li>
          <li>
            <m>\int \cos(t)\dx{t}</m>
          </li>
          <li>
            <m>\int \sec(t)\tan(t)\dx{t}</m>
          </li>
          <li>
            <m>\int e^t\dx{t}</m>
          </li>
          <li>
            <m>\int t^{-1}\dx{t}</m>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </problem>

    <exercise xml:id="EXERCISEAntiDerivPractice">
      <introduction>
        <p>
          <idx><h>Antiderivative</h></idx>
          Show that  the following statements are true. Assume
          <m>C</m> is an arbitrary constant.
        </p>
      </introduction>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            <m>\int 2te^{t^2}\dx{t} = e^{t^2} +C</m>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            <m>\int te^t\dx{t} = (t-1)e^t+C</m>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            <m>\int \sin(x)\cos(x)\dx{x} =\frac12\sin^2(x)+C</m>
          </p>
        </statement>
<hint>
          <p>
            Notice that we<rsq/>ve used <m>x</m> instead of <m>t</m> for our
            variable. Does that matter? Explain.
          </p>
</hint>
      </task>
      <task  xml:id="PROBLEMSinsqcossqantider">
        <statement>
          <p>
            <m>\int \sin(\theta )\cos(\theta )\dx{\theta } =
            -\frac12\cos^2(\theta )+C</m>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            <m>\int u\cos(u) \dx{u} = u\sin(u)+\cos(u)+C</m>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            <m>\int x\ln(x) \dx{x} = x(\ln{x}-1)+C</m>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </task>


    </exercise>

    <!-- <paragraphs> -->
    <!--   <title>Where Did the Summation Go?</title> -->
    <!--   <p> -->
    <!--     You may have noticed that while we have taken considerable -->
    <!--     care to bolster the notion that <q>integration is addition,</q> all  -->
    <!--     of our examples and problems  emphasized that  -->
    <!--     <q>integration is antidifferentiation.</q> We will hold to -->
    <!--     this viewpoint until <xref provisional="section on definite integration"></xref> -->
    <!--   </p> -->
    <!-- </paragraphs> -->
  </subsection>
  </section>

  <section>
    <title>Rules for Integration</title>
    <p>
      Since integration can be thought of as the reverse of
      Differentiation it is not too surprising to learn that each
      differentiation rule has its integration rule counterpart.  The
      following table illustrates in both their differential and
      integral form the rules we have already seen.
    </p>
    
    <table xml:id="TABLEBasicIntegration">
      <title>Integration Rules Inherited from Differentiation Rules</title>
      <tabular halign="center">
        <row bottom="major" header="yes">
          
          <cell></cell><cell>Differentiation Rule</cell><cell><line>Integration
          Rule</line><line> (Assume <m>a</m> and <m>c</m> are
          constants.)  </line></cell>
        </row>
        <row>
          <cell>1</cell>          <cell><m>\dx(\text{constant})=0</m></cell>
          <cell><line><m>\int0\dx{x}=c,</m></line> <line> where <m> c
          </m> is a constant.</line></cell>
        </row>
        <row>
          <cell>2</cell>          <cell><m>\dx(f+g)=\dx{f}+\dx{g}</m></cell>
          <cell><line><m>\int\dx(f+g)=\int\dx{f}+\int\dx{g}</m></line>
          <line><m>=f+g+c</m></line></cell>
        </row>
        <row>
          <cell>3</cell>          <cell><line>If <m>a</m> is a constant, then</line>
          <line><m>\dx(ay)=a\dx(y)</m></line>
        </cell>
        <cell>
          <line><m>\int a\dx{y}=\int\dx(ay)=a\int\dx{y}</m></line>
        <line><m>=ay+c</m></line></cell>
        </row>
        <row>
          <cell>4</cell>          <cell><m>\dx(x^{n+1})=(n+1)x^n\dx{x}</m></cell>
          <cell><m>\int x^n\dx{x} = \frac{x^{n+1}}{n+1}+c, n\neq
          -1</m></cell>
        </row>
        <row>
          <cell>5</cell>          <cell><m>\dx(\ln(x))=\frac1x\dx{x}=x^{-1}\dx{x}</m></cell>
          <cell><m>\int x^{-1}\dx{x} = \ln\abs{x}+c</m></cell>
        </row>
        <row>
          <cell>6</cell>          <cell><m>\dx(e^x)= e^x\dx{x}</m></cell>
          <cell><m>\int e^x\dx{x} = e^x+c</m></cell>
        </row>
        <row>
          <cell>7</cell>          <cell><m>\dx(\sin(x))=\cos(x)\dx{x}</m></cell>
          <cell><m>\int \cos(x) = \sin(x) +c</m></cell>
        </row>
        <row>
          <cell>8</cell>          <cell><m>\dx(\cos(x))=-\sin(x)\dx{x}</m></cell>
          <cell><m>\int \sin(x)\dx{x} = -\cos(x) +c</m></cell>
        </row>
        <row>
          <cell>9</cell>          <cell><m>\dx(\tan(x))=\sec^2(x)\dx{x}</m></cell>
          <cell><m>\int\sec^2(x)\dx{x} = \tan(x)+c</m></cell>
        </row>
        <row>
          <cell>10</cell>          <cell><m>\dx(\sec(x))= \sec(x)\tan(x)\dx{x}</m></cell>
          <cell><m>\int\sec(x)\tan(x)=\sec(x)+c</m></cell>
        </row>
        <row>
          <cell>11</cell>          <cell><m>\dx(\inverse\sin(x))=
          \frac{1}{\sqrt{1-x^2}}\dx{x}</m></cell>
          <cell><m>\int\frac{1}{\sqrt{1-x^2}}\dx{x}=\inverse\sin(x)+c</m></cell>
        </row>
        <row>
          <cell>12</cell>          <cell><m>\dx(\inverse\tan(x))=
          \frac{1}{1+x^2}\dx{x}</m></cell>
          <cell><m>\int\frac{1}{1+x^2}\dx{x}=\inverse\tan(x)+c</m></cell>
        </row>
        <row>
          <cell>13</cell>          <cell><m>\dx(\inverse\sec(x))=
          \frac{1}{x\sqrt{x^2-1}}\dx{x}</m></cell>
          <cell><m>\int\frac{1}{x\sqrt{x^2-1}}\dx{x}=\inverse\sec(x)+c</m></cell>
        </row>
      </tabular>
    </table>
    
    
<p>
A few comments on lines <m>4</m> and <m>5</m> from <xref ref="TABLEBasicIntegration"></xref> are in
order.
</p>
    <!-- <p> -->
    <!--   <xref ref="TABLEBasicIntegration">Table</xref> is not -->
    <!--   exhaustive. It couldn<rsq/>t possibly be since every -->
    <!--   differentiation formula gives rise to a corresponding -->
    <!--   integration formula. -->
    <!-- </p> -->
    <!-- <p> -->
    <!--   Conspicuously absent from <xref -->
    <!--   ref="TABLEBasicIntegration">Table</xref> are the Product Rule, the -->
    <!--   Quotient Rule, and the Chain Rule.  The reverse of the Quotient Rule -->
    <!--   is rather limited in its applicability and typically is not used. -->
    <!--   Reversing the others can be quite useful and will be covered -->
    <!--   later. -->
    <!-- </p> -->
    <!-- <p> -->
    <!--   If you read each of these Differentiation and Integration Rules -->
    <!--   verbally you can hear that they reverse each other. For example in -->
    <!--   line 4 we see that to differentiate <m>x</m> to a power, we -->
    <!--   <q>multiply by the exponent and then subtract one from the -->
    <!--   exponent.</q> To reverse the process notice that everything gets run -->
    <!--   backwards: We first <q>add one to the exponent, then we divide by -->
    <!--   the exponent.</q> (In the same way that when dressing you put your -->
    <!--   socks on and then your shoes and to reverse it you take off your -->
    <!--     shoes first and then your socks).  -->
    <!-- </p> -->
    <p>
      Notice that the Integration Rule in line 4 will not work if the
      exponent is <m>n=-1</m> as you cannot divide by zero. But that
      apparent hole is covered on line 5. Does it seem odd to
      you that the we need the natural logarithm to plug that hole? After
      all, line 4 is about powers of the variable, which is a fairly
      concrete idea, whereas the natural logarithm function is much more
      abstract
    </p>
    
    <exercise>
      <statement>
    <p>
      While we are at line five, notice that we have
      inserted an absolute value in the formula:
      <me>
        \int\inverse x\dx{x}=\ln\abs{x}+C.
      </me> 
          <!-- One way to define the absolute value function is -->
          <!-- <m>\abs{x}=\sqrt{x^2}</m> where the radical indicates the -->
          <!-- non-negative square root.  For example, -->
          <!-- <m>\abs{3}=\sqrt{(3^2)}=\sqrt{(9)}=3</m> and -->
          <!-- <m>\abs{-3}=\sqrt{(-3)^2}=\sqrt{9}=3</m>. -->
        </p>
        <p>
We saw in <xref ref="DIGRESSIONAbsValSqrt">DIGRESSION: The Absolute Value Function</xref>  that an
alternative definition of the absolute value function is
<me>\abs{x}=\sqrt{x^2}</me>.
          Show if we use this definition  we still
          obtain the formula
          <me>
            \dx(\ln\abs{x})=\frac1x \dx{x}
          </me>.
        </p>
        <p>
          (It is  common to write <m>\int\inverse
          x\dx{x}=\ln(x)+C</m>, even though this is only valid for
          <m>x\gt{0}</m>.  We will adopt this practice.)
        </p>
      </statement>
      <hint>
        <p>
          Be careful that you do not try to take the logarithm of a
          negative number.
        </p>
      </hint>
    </exercise>
    
    
    <problem>
      <p>
        It looks like we broke our own rule in lines two and three in
        the above table of integration rules.  Don<rsq/>t we need two
        integration constants? Isn<rsq/>t it true that
        <me>
          \int \dx{f} +\int \dx{g} = f+c_1+g+c_2
        </me>
        where <m>c_1</m>and <m>c_2</m> are arbitrary constants, and that
        <me>
          a\int\dx{y}=a(y+c)=ay+ac </me>.
          Explain why what we have in the table is still legitimate.
      </p>
    </problem>
    
    <p>
      In light of the above problem, practitioners will often
      integrate each term of a differential and then combineany
      arbitrary constants into one constant.  For example,
      consider
      
      <md>
        <mrow>
          \int\left(5x^2-3\sqrt{x}+\frac{2}{1+x^2}\right)\dx{x}\amp
          =5\int x^2\dx{x}-3\int x^\frac12
          \dx{x}+2\int\frac{1}{1+x^2}\dx{x}
        </mrow>
        <mrow>
          \amp =5\left(\frac{x^3}{3}\right) -
          \frac{3\left(x^{\frac12}\right)}{\frac32} +
          2\inverse\tan(x)+c
        </mrow>
        <mrow>
          \amp =\frac53x^3-2x^{\frac32}+2\inverse\tan(x)+c.
        </mrow>
      </md>
      As with differentiation, when you get more comfortable
      with integration, you will probably do many of these steps in your
      head.  But that ability will only come with practice.
    </p>
<p>
Integrals come up in a variety of situations. To take a very simple
example, suppose we know that the derivative of some function
</p>
  </section>

  <section  xml:id="SECTIONDiffeqsIVPS">
    <title>Differential Equations</title>

    <p>
<idx><h>Terminology</h><h>Differential Equation</h></idx>

      Differential Calculus gives us an extraordinarily powerful set
      of tools for modeling real world phenomena. We saw some simple
      examples of this when we studied differentiation. For example,
      suppose we have a body with mass equal to one kilogram falling
      freely under the force of the earth<rsq/>s gravitational
      pull. we know that the acceleration, <m>a</m> of the body is  the
       derivative of its velocity, <m>v</m>, so: <m>a=\dfdx{v}{t}</m>. Moreover
      we saw in <xref ref="SECTIONGalileoDrops"></xref> that Galileo
      found that a body falling freely near the surface of the earth
      would accelerate downward at a constant rate we<rsq/>ve called
      <m>g</m>. This is fully described by the <term>
      differential equation</term>

      <men xml:id="EQUATIONFallingBodyModel">\dfdx{v}{t}=g,</men>

      which is a simple model of the motion of a falling body. 
</p>

    <p>
      The simplest differential equations to solve are those, like
      <xref ref="EQUATIONFallingBodyModel">equation</xref> where the
      derivative of a function, say <m>y(t)</m>, is given entirely in
      terms of of the variable, <m>t</m> in this case. In general such
      equations can be written in the form
      <me>
        \dfdx{y}{t} = f(t)
        </me> 
        where <m>f(t)</m> is some known function. <xref
        ref="EQUATIONFallingBodyModel">Equation</xref> is particularly
        simple since not even the variable appears in <m>f(t)=g</m>,
        only the constant <m>g</m>.
    </p>
<p>
We solve this differential equation as follows

<mdn>
<mrow number="no">
  \dfdx{y}{t}\amp{}= f(t)
</mrow>
<mrow  xml:id="EQUATIONSimplestDiffeq">
\dx{y}\amp{}=f(t)\dx{t}
</mrow>
</mdn>.
<xref ref="EQUATIONSimplestDiffeq">Equation</xref>  says that the
differential <m>\dx{y} </m> is equal to the differential
<m>f(x)\dx{t}
</m>.
Adding all of the differentials on both sides of <xref
ref="EQUATIONSimplestDiffeq">equation</xref> we have
<me>
\int \dx{y}=\int f(t)\dx{t}
</me>
 and from this we see that
<me>
y=\int f(t)\dx{t}{}
</me>.
Thus to solve <xref ref="EQUATIONFallingBodyModel">equation</xref> we
need only find an antiderivative of <m>f(t)</m>.

</p>


<p>
Notice that <xref ref="EQUATIONFallingBodyModel">Equation</xref> is a
very simple manifestation of Newton<rsq/>s Second Law: <m>F\text{orce}
= M\text{ass}\cdot A\text{cceleration}</m>. 
</p>
<p>
Since the only force acting on the body is gravity, (<m>g</m>), we see
that the total force, <m>F=m\dfdxn{y}{t}{2} </m> is equal to <m>g</m>,
or 
<me>F=m\dfdxn{y}{t}{2} = g</me>, but since <m>m=1</m> this reduces to 
<xref ref="EQUATIONFallingBodyModel">equation</xref>.it e
</p>

<p>


From
      this model we can recover functions which tell us the velocity
      and the position of a falling body at any time and under any
      starting conditions (see <xref
      ref="SECTIONGalileoDrops"></xref>).  We will have more to say
      about this particular model in <xref
      ref="SECTIONProjectileMotion"></xref>.
    </p>
<!-- <paragraphs> -->
<!-- <title>DIGRESSION: The Order of a Differential Equation</title> -->
<!-- <p> -->
<!-- We called  -->
<!-- <xref ref="EQUATIONFallingBodyModel">equation</xref> -->
<!-- <q>second order </q> because <m>\dx^2{y} </m> is the highest -->
<!-- order differential  appearing.  -->
<!-- </p> -->
<!-- <p> -->
<!-- This -->
<!-- text is not about differential equations  -->
<!-- <foreign>per se,</foreign> but many of the <q>calculus problems</q> -->
<!-- that come to us from nature arrive in the form of a differential -->
<!-- equation, so it will be useful for us to become acquainted with the -->
<!-- language of differential equations, and some of of the simpler -->
<!-- solution techniques. Most of the the differential equations -->
<!-- we<rsq/>ll see will be first order. -->
<!-- </p> -->
<!-- <p> -->
<!-- However higher order differential -->
<!-- equations will come up occasionally (see -->
<!-- for example, <xref ref="SECTIONEulerHarmonicOsc"></xref>). -->
<!-- </p> -->
<!-- <p> -->
<!-- Finally,  the term <term>differential equation</term> is an historical artifact. They -->
<!--  should really be called <q>derivative</q> equations because they -->
<!--  almost always involve the differential ratios we<rsq/>ve called -->
<!--  <q>derivatives</q>. -->
<!-- </p> -->


<!-- <p><alert>END OF DIGRESSION</alert></p> -->
<!-- </paragraphs> -->




    <p>
      In <xref ref="PROBLEMHangingChain"></xref> of <xref ref="SECTIONhyperb-trig-hang"></xref> we saw
      that if <m>y(x)</m> is the shape that a hanging chain naturally
      settles into under the pull of gravity then <m>y(x)</m> will
      necessarily be a solution of the second order differential equation:
      <men  xml:id="EQUATIONHangChainModel">
        \dfdxn{y}{x}{2} =
        \frac{w}{H}\sqrt{1+\left(\dfdx{y}{x}\right)^2}.
      </men>
      which is a model for the Hanging Chain problem. That is, the graph of a
      function which solves <xref ref="EQUATIONHangChainModel">equation</xref> will
      be  the shape of a hanging chain.
    </p>

    <problem  xml:id="DRILLHangingChainSolution">
      <p>
        Show that               <men  xml:id="EQUATIONCatenary2">
        y=\frac{H}{w}
        \left(\frac{e^{\frac{wx}{H}}+e^{-\frac{wx}{H}}}{2}\right)
      </men>
      solves <xref ref="EQUATIONHangChainModel">equation</xref>.
(This is a repeat of <xref ref="PROBLEMHangChainD">Problem</xref>.)
</p>
    </problem>



    <p>
      It is one thing to confirm a given solution, as in <xref
      ref="DRILLHangingChainSolution"></xref>, but finding the solution in
      the first place is not at all a simple task.  A start might be to let
      <m>z=\dfdx{y}{x}</m>, so we have
      
      <mdn>
        <mrow number="no">
          \dfdx{z}{x}\amp=\frac{w}{H}\sqrt{1+z^2}
        </mrow>
        <mrow xml:id="EQUATIONHangingChainInt1">
          \frac{1}{\sqrt{1+z^2}}\dx{z}\amp =\frac{w}{H}\dx{x}
        </mrow>
      </mdn>.
As we saw in <xref ref="DIGRESSIONDifferentialNotation">DIGRESSION:
Differential Notation</xref> the product of a number and a
differential is a differential so 
      <xref ref="EQUATIONHangingChainInt1">equation</xref> says that every
      differential of the form <m>\frac{1}{\sqrt{1+z^2}}\dx{z}</m> is
      equal to a differential of the form <m>\frac{w}{H}\dx{z}
      </m>. Thus, if we add  all of the differentials  on both sides of <xref
      ref="EQUATIONHangingChainInt1">equation</xref>,  equality will be
      retained. That is,
      <men  xml:id="EQUATIONHangingChainInt2">
        \int\frac{1}{\sqrt{1+z^2}}\dx{z}=\int\frac{w}{H}\dx{x}
      </men>.
    </p>
    
    <p>
      The right-hand side of <xref ref="EQUATIONHangingChainInt2">equation</xref>  doesn<rsq/>t pose any problems. Since
      <m>w</m> and <m>H</m> are both constants, it follows that
      <m>\frac{w}{H}</m> is also a constant. Thus we see that row 3 of
      <xref ref="TABLEBasicIntegration"></xref> applies, and <m>\int
      \frac{w}{H}\dx{x} = \frac{w}{H}t+C </m>. We still need to find
      the value of the constant <m>C</m>, but that is usually pretty
      straighforward as you will see soon.
    </p>
    <p>
      But the left-hand side isn<rsq/>t as easy.  It doesn't quite
      match anything in <xref ref="TABLEBasicIntegration"></xref> so
      we currently have no way to address it. We need a new idea, so
      we will come back to this once we<rsq/>ve developed some more
      sophisticated techniques.
    </p>
    <aside>
      <title>A Little Encouragement</title>
      <p>
        In the meantime see if you can find a way to compute
        <m>\int\frac{1}{\sqrt{1+z^2}}\dx{z}</m>. Come up with an
        idea, give it a try, and see what happens. The learning is
        in the trying, not the succeeding.
      </p>
    </aside>
    
    <p>
      Our goal in this chapter is to develop techniques that will enable us
      to compute various integrals like the ones we<rsq/>ve just seen. These
      integration techniques are the tools that will enable us to solve
      (some) differential equations.
      <!-- ust see s this integral soon, but first -->
      <!--  let's look at some applications of integration which use what we -->
      <!--  already know how to do. -->
    </p>

<!-- <p> -->
<!-- Recall <xref ref="DEFINITIONIVP"></xref> -->
<!-- </p> -->
<!--     <definition xml:id="DEFINITIONIVP2"> -->
<!--       <title>Initial Value Problem (IVP)</title> -->
<!--       <statement> -->
<!--         <p> -->
<!--           <!-\- \label{def:IVP} -\-> -->
<!--           An <term>Initial Value Problem</term> is a differential -->
<!--           equation of the form <me>\dfdx{y}{x}=f(x,y),</me> along with -->
<!--           an <term>Initial Value</term> <me>y(x_0)=y_0.</me> -->
<!--         </p> -->
<!--       </statement> -->
<!--     </definition> -->


  </section>

  <section  xml:id="SECTIONSubstMethed">
    <title>Accounting for  Resistance – This Looks Like a Job for
    Substitution!</title>
    <p>
      To keep things simple we have ignored air resistance so
      far. But, depending on the conditions, resistance can have a
      substantial effect on a body<rsq/>s motion. So we need to
      account for it in our model.
    </p>
    <p>
      In general, the faster the body is moving through a fluid (like
      air or water) the more the fluie tends to resist the
      motion. Hence the resistive force, or <term>drag</term>, is
      most simply modeled as a function of the
      body<rsq/>svelocity. You can experience this directly by holding
      your hand out a car window.  The faster the car moves, the more
      force you will feel on your hand. Similarly, the faster you move
      your hand under water, the more force you will feel resisting
      the motion.
    </p>
    <p>
      Many phenomena will affect drag (speed, viscosity of the medium,
      shape and size of the object, turbulence).  For a medium with a
      relatively high viscosity and a relatively small object the
      assumption that the drag is proportional to the velocity of the
      object makes for a reasonably accurate model.  An example of this is
      a grain of sand falling in water.
    </p>
    <p>
      For a medium with a relatively low viscosity, such as
      air, and a relatively large object, the drag is assumed to be
      proportional to the square of the velocity.  This would be the
      model to use for a baseball falling in the air.
    </p>
    <p>
      Of course  to get a really accurate picture, we could use both a linear
      term and a quadratic term to represent the drag, but we will
      keep things as
      simple as possible for now.  In our first example we<rsq/>ll
      assume that the resistive force is proportional to
      velocity. This is called
      <term>linear drag</term>. 
    </p>
    <example xml:id="EXAMPLESandInWater">
      <p>
        To model a grain of sand with mass <m>m</m> descending in water
        we let <m>y(t)</m> be distance the sand has fallen (so the
        positive <m>y</m> axis is pointing downward), with
        <m>y(0)=0</m> representing the surface of the water. From the
        diagram below we see that there are three forces acting on
        the sand: (1) the weight of the sand grain, (2) the buoyancy of the
        sand grain, and (3) the drag that the water imposes on the
        sand grain.
      </p>
      <p>
        The total force acting on the grain, <m>F=m\dfdxn{y}{t}{2} </m>, will
        be equal to the sum of these three forces.
      </p>
      <image source="IC/Boyancy1.png" width="25%">
        <shortdescription>Diagram of the forces on an object in a
        fluid.</shortdescription>
      </image>
      <p>
        As always we denote the acceleration due to gravity by
        <m>g</m>.
        Then the weight of the sand is <m>mg</m>.  The drag, which we
        assume is linear, is proportional to the velocity, so we will
        denote this by <m>-Rv</m>, where <m>R</m> is a positive constant and
        <m>v=\dfdx{y}{t}</m> is the velocity.  Notice that this force
        is negative as the drag is necessarily in the direction
        opposite  of the motion.
      </p>
      <p>
        Since we have not discussed buoyancy before, a short explanation is in
        order.  The buoyancy of an object is force that a surrounding fluid
        applies to it. This force is equal to the weight of the fluid being
        displaced by the object. If the density of the object is less than the
        density of water then the weight of the object and it<rsq/>s boyancy
        will balance before the object is completely covered by the
        fluid. That is, the object floats.
      </p>
      <aside>
        <title>Note to self</title>
        <p>
          Is more explanation necessary here?
        </p>
      </aside>


    </example>
    
    <exercise  xml:id="PROBLEMTerminalVeloctiy">
      <title>Terminal Velocity</title>

      <task>
        <p>
          Use Newton's Second Law to show that the situation in <xref
          ref="EXAMPLESandInWater"></xref> can be modeled by the IVP
          <md>
            <mrow>
              m\dfdx{v}{t}=(m-m_w)g-Rv,\amp{}\amp{}
              v(0)=v_0.
            </mrow>
          </md>
        </p>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Let <m>M=m-m_w</m> and note that <m>M\gt0</m>.
            (why?) Show that the above leads to the IVP
            <md>
              <mrow>
                \frac{\dx{v}}{Rv-Mg}=\frac{-1}{m}\dx{t}\amp{}\amp{}
                v(0)=v_0.
              </mrow>
            </md>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </task>
      
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Use the substitution <m>z=Rv-Mg</m>, to rewrite the above
            equation as
            <me>
              \frac{\frac{1}{R}\dx{z}}{z}=-\frac{1}{m}\dx{t}.
            </me>
          </p>

        </statement>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
              Show that
              <m>
                v=\frac{Mg}{R}+\left(v_0-\frac{Mg}{R}\right)e^{-\frac{R}{m}t}.
              </m>
            </p>

        </statement>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Compute <m>\limit{t}{\infty}{v}</m>, and explain why this
            is called  the
            <term>terminal velocity</term> of the sand settling in the
            water. Notice that the terminal velocity is  independent of
            <m>v_0</m>.  Does this make
            sense physically? Explain.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </task>
    </exercise>
    
    <paragraphs xml:id="PARAGRAPHSubstGBU">
      <title> Substitution, the Good, the Bad, and the Ugly</title>

      <p>
        <xref ref="PROBLEMTerminalVeloctiy"></xref> uses the technique of
        substitution. When we were learning differentiation  we  called this <q>making things easier on the
        eyes</q>  because in that context
        the substitutions we made almost always resulted in simpler formulas
        that were easier to deal with than the originals..
      </p>
      <p>
        Our goal when making a substitution is to
        simplify things
        <em>eventually</em>. But sometimes things will get more complicated
        first. We will proceed slowly.
      </p>
      <example xml:id="EXAMPLEIntTan">
        <title>The Integral of the Tangent Function</title>

        <p>
          One of the entries in <xref ref="TABLEBasicIntegration"></xref>,
          was <m>\int\sin(x)\dx{x} = -\cos(x)+c</m>. We can use this to
          compute  <m>\int\tan(x)\dx{x}</m> by making the substitution

          <md>
            <mrow>
              z=\cos(x),
            </mrow>
            <intertext>which means that</intertext>
            <mrow>\dx{z}=-\sin(x)\dx{x}</mrow>
            <intertext> or</intertext>
            <mrow>\textcolor{red}{-\dx{z}=\sin(x)\dx{z}}</mrow>
            </md>.
        </p>
        <p>
          Thus
          <md>
            <mrow>\int\tan(x)\dx{x} =
            \int\frac{\textcolor{red}{\sin(x)}}{\cos(x)}\textcolor{red}{\dx{x}}
            <!-- \amp -->
            <!--            =\int\frac{\sin(x)}{z}\cdot\frac{-\dx{z}}{\sin(x)}</mrow> -->
            \amp =-\int\frac{\dx{z}}{z}
            </mrow>
            <mrow>\amp =-\ln(z)+c</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp =(-1)\ln(\cos(x))+c</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp =\ln\left((\cos(x))^{-1}\right)+c</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp =\ln\left(\sec(x)\right)+c</mrow>
            </md>.
        </p>
      </example>
      <problem>
        <p>
          Use a similar substitution to show that
          <me>\int\cot(x)\dx{x}=-\ln(\csc(x)+c</me>
        </p>
      </problem>


      <p>
        Making a substitution in an integral is just the first
        step. We still have to compute the integral. Our substitution
        just
        makes it a little  simpler to apply formulas and techniques with which we
        are already familiar.  As simple as it is, substitution is no
        mere trick. It is a very powerful technique, not just in
        differentiation an integration but in all of mathematics.
      </p>
      <p>
        The good news is that you can do any substitution you wish and
        as long as it is performed correctly, it is not wrong.
      </p>
      <p>
        But the bad news is that you can do any substitution you wish
        and as long as it is performed correctly, it is not wrong.
      </p>
      <p>
        That is to say, you can make any substitution you wish.  As
        long as all calculations are done correctly, it will not be
        <em>wrong</em> in any absolute sense. But it may not be
        helpful either and it won<rsq/>t always be easy to tell until
        you<rsq/>ve done a lot of computations whether the
        substitution you chose is viable. This issue will be mitigated
        as you gain experience but, especially in the beginning, be
        careful.  It is very easy to make what looks like a reasonable
        substitution which is either unworkable or, if it is workable,
        is much harder to do than different substitution would be.
      </p>

      <p>
        For example, when computing
        <m>\int\tan(x)\dx{x}</m>, we could have let <m>z=x</m>. In that
        case we would have <m>\int\tan(x)\dx{x}=\int\tan(z)\dx{z}</m>
        which is true, but it  is not helpful.
      </p>
      <p>
        Another approach would be to let <m>u=\tan(x)</m> so that
        <m>\dx{u}=\sec^2(x)\dx{x}</m> or <m>\dx{x} =\frac{\dx{u}
        }{\sec^2(x) }</m>. In that case we have
        <mdn>
          <mrow number="no">
            \int\tan(x)\dx{x}\amp{}=\int\frac{u}{\sec^2(x)}\dx{u}
          </mrow>
          <mrow number="no">
            \amp{}=\int\frac{u}{1+\tan^2(x)}\dx{u}
          </mrow>
          <intertext>so that</intertext>
          <mrow xml:id="EQUATIONBadTanInt1">
            \int\tan(x)\dx{x}=\amp{}=\int\frac{u}{1+u^2}\dx{u}
          </mrow>
          </mdn>.
      </p>
      <p>
        This is a true statement <mdash/> we haven<rsq/>t made any
        computational errors <mdash/> but it appears that after the
        substitution we will need to evaluate <m>\int
        \frac{u}{1+u^2}\dx{y}</m>, which looks hard. It is actually
        possible to compute this integral using the knowledge you now
        have. It is simply a matter of finding the right
        substitution. However, since we have already computed <m>\int
        \tan(x) \dx{x}</m> in <xref ref="EXAMPLEIntTan"></xref> it is
        pointless to continue with this example.
      </p>
      <!-- <p> -->
      <!-- However knowing that  -->
      <!-- <men xml:id="EQUATIONIntTan3"> -->
      <!-- \int\tan(x)\dx{x}=\int\frac{u}{\sec^2(x)}\dx{u}=\int\frac{u}{1+u^2}\dx{u}.</men> -->
      <!-- will be helpful to us in <xref -->
      <!-- ref="PROBLEMTrickySubstitution1"></xref> below so we take specific -->
      <!-- notice of this fact here. -->
      <!-- </p> -->
      <!-- <p> -->


      <!-- This is an  integral you can do today if you are clever enough, but it will require that you make another substitution. Since we<rsq/>ve already done at least as much work to get to <xref ref="EQUATIONBadTanInt1">equation</xref> as we did  this approach seems like it -->
      <!--         will be much harder than our original strategy so we're -->
      <!--         inclined to abandon it immediately. -->
      <!--       </p> -->
      <p>
        A comparably bad choice is   <m>u=\sin(x)</m>. With this
        substitution we have
        <m>\dx{u}=\cos(x)\dx{x}</m> or
        <m>\dx{x}=\frac{\dx{u}}{\cos(x)}</m>. In this case we have
        <mdn>
          <mrow number="no"> 
            \int\tan(x)\dx{x} =\amp{} \int\frac{\sin(x)}{\cos(x)}\dx{x}
          </mrow>
          <mrow xml:id="EQUATIONBadTanInt2">
            \amp{}= \int\left(\frac{u}{\cos(x)}\cdot\frac{\dx{u}}{\cos(x)}\right)
            =\int\frac{u}{1-u^2}\dx{u}
          </mrow>
        </mdn>
        which is nearly the same, formally, as <xref ref="EQUATIONBadTanInt1">
        equation</xref>. The only difference seems to be that the
        <q><m>+</m></q> in the denominator in <xref
        ref="EQUATIONBadTanInt1">equation</xref> became a
        <q><m>-</m></q> in <xref
        ref="EQUATIONBadTanInt2">equation</xref>.
      </p>
      <aside>
        <title>Observation</title>
        <p>
          We say <q>formally</q> because they aren't really the
          same. We<rsq/>ve used the substitution variable <m>u</m> to
          represent two entirely different functions in each of these
          formula.
        </p>
      </aside>
      <exercise xml:id="PROBLEMTrickySubstitution1">
        <introduction>
          <p>
            On the other hand we  know from <xref ref="EXAMPLEIntTan"></xref> that
            <m>\int\tan(x)\dx{x}=\ln(\sec(x)+c</m> and we can use this
            knowledge.
          </p>
          <p>
            Suppose we need to compute
            <m>\int\frac{u}{1+u^2}\dx{u}</m> or
            <m>\int\frac{u}{1-u^2}\dx{u}</m>. The same substitution we
            used to transform <m>\int\tan(x)\dx{x}</m> these into the
            integrals (seen in <xref
            ref="EQUATIONBadTanInt1">equation</xref> and <xref
            ref="EQUATIONBadTanInt2">equation</xref>)
            will work in reverse.
          </p>
        </introduction>
        <task  xml:id="PROBLEMTrickySubstitution1A">
          <statement>
            <p>
              Use the substitution <m>u=\tan(x)</m> to show that:
              <me>
                \int\frac{u}{1+u^2}\dx{u} =
                \ln\left(\sec\left(\inverse\tan(u)\right)\right)+c.
              </me>
            </p>
            <p>
              Now use your Algebra and Trigonometry skills to show that
              <m>\sec\left(\inverse\tan(u)\right) = \sqrt{1+u^2}</m> so
              that <me> \int\frac{u}{1+u^2}\dx{u} =
              \frac12\ln\left(1+u^2\right)+c</me>.
            </p>
          </statement>
        </task>
        
        <task xml:id="PROBLEMTrickySubstitution1B">
          <statement>
            <p>
              Use the substitution <m>u=\sin(x)</m> to show that
              <me>
                \int\frac{u}{1-u^2}\dx{u}=
                \ln\left(\sec\left(\inverse\sin(u)\right)\right)+c.
              </me>
            </p>
            <p>
              Now use your Algebra and Trigonometry skills to show that
              <m>\sec\left(\inverse\sin(u)\right) = \sqrt{1-u^2}</m> so
              that <me> \int\frac{u}{1-u^2}\dx{u} =
              -\frac{1}{2}\ln\left(1-u^2\right)+c</me>.
            </p>
          </statement>
        </task>
        
      </exercise>
      <aside>
        <title>Advice and Encouragement</title>
        <p>
          You have surely noticed that the calculations you had to do
          to evaluate the integrals in <xref
          ref="PROBLEMTrickySubstitution1">Problem</xref> were quite
          intricate. Not hard, <foreign> per se, </foreign> but there
          were a lot of steps and at each point you had to draw on just
          the right tool from Algebra, or Trigonometry, or Differential
          Calculus.
        </p>
        
        <p> For example, to get the one-half factor out in front you
        needed first to recognize that <m>\sqrt{x}=x^{1/2}</m> and then
        you needed the following property of logarithms:
        <m>\ln(a^b)=b\ln(a)</m>.
        </p>
        
        <p>
          This is what your math courses are going to be like from now
          on. You will continue to learn new techniques and acquire new
          tools.  But the new material will frequently be fairly simple
          to <em> understand<em></em> </em> but not so simple to
          implement. When struggling with a problem it is easy to make
          the mistake of thinking that you must have misunderstood the
          new material, but it will frequently be the case that you you
          really just don't see which is the right tool to use, or how
          to use it.
          
        </p>
        <p>
          This will be frustrating at times. Don't give up. Ask for
          help if you need it. But be patient with yourself. When you
          are deep into a problem it is easy to overlook simple things,
          and then to be embarrassed when your teacher or a classmate
          shows you that all you had to do was factor out an
          <m>x</m>. When this happens just learn the lesson, remember
          it, and move on. There is no need for embarassment and it
          will only waste your time and sap your self-confidence. We've
          all been there.
        </p>
      </aside>
      
      <exercise xml:id="PROBLEMAlgebraicSubst1">
        <introduction>
          <p>
            The integrals in <xref ref="PROBLEMTrickySubstitution1A"> Problem </xref> and
            <xref ref="PROBLEMTrickySubstitution1B"> Problem </xref> can be evaluated by
            means of several different substitutions as we've seen.
            There are others that will also work but our principle
            point for now is that no substitution is <q>wrong</q>, some
            result in a new integral that is easier than the original
            and some will not. If our goal is simply to evaluate the
            integral we'll want to look for the simplest method we can
            find.
          </p>
        </introduction>
        
        <task xml:id="PROBLEMAlgebraicSubst1A">
          <statement>
            <p>
              Find a simpler substitution than the one we used in <xref
              ref="PROBLEMTrickySubstitution1A">Problem</xref> to evaluate the integral
              <me>
                \int\frac{x}{1+x^2}\dx{x}
              </me>
            </p>
          </statement>
          <!-- <hint> -->
          <!--   <p> -->
          <!--     Notice that we're back to using <m>x</m> as the -->
          <!--     variable. Does this matter? -->
          <!--   </p> -->
          <!-- </hint> -->
          <hint>
            <p>
              Notice that <m>x\dx{x}</m> is <em>almost</em> the
              differential of <m>1+x^2</m>.
            </p>
          </hint>
        </task>
        <task  xml:id="PROBLEMAlgebraicSubst1B">
          <statement>
            <p>
              Find a simpler substitution than the one we used in <xref
              ref="PROBLEMTrickySubstitution1B">Problem</xref> to evaluate the integral
              <me>
                \int\frac{x}{1-x^2}\dx{x}
              </me>
            </p>
          </statement>
          <hint>
            <p>The substitution you used in <xref
            ref="PROBLEMAlgebraicSubst1A"></xref> will probably work here.</p>
          </hint>
        </task>
      </exercise>

      <p>
        A good
        <url href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rule_of_thumb" visual="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rule_of_thumb">Rule of Thumb</url>
        for choosing a substitution is to look a the
        <term>integrand</term> (the part between <m>\int </m> and the
        differential) and see if you can find an expression and its
        derivative. That is how we chose the substitution <m>z=\cos(x) </m> in
        <xref ref="EXAMPLEIntTan"></xref>, and what the hints in <xref
        ref="PROBLEMAlgebraicSubst1"></xref> tried to lead you to. If you
        can<rsq/>t find an expression and its derivative try to find an
        expression and
        <em>almost</em> its derivative.
      </p>

      <example>
        <task>
          <title>An Unhelpful Substitution</title>
          <p>
            For example, consider the integral

            <me> \int       x^2\sqrt{x^3+1}\dx{x} </me>

            We  let <m>u = x^2</m> so that
            <m>\dx{u} = 2x \dx{x}</m>. This gives

            <md>
              <mrow> \int   x^2\sqrt{x^3+1}\dx{x}= \int
              u\sqrt{u^{3/2}+1}\left(\frac{\dx{u}}{2x}\right)</mrow>
              <intertext> Notice
              that we can bring the <m>1/2</m> outside the integral because
              it is a constant, but since <m>\frac{1}{x}</m> is not a
              constant (it depends on <m>u</m>) we cannot do the same with
              with it so</intertext>
              <mrow> \amp{}=
              \frac12\int\frac{u\sqrt{u^{3/2}+1}}{x}\dx{u}.</mrow>
              <intertext>
                We could rewrite <m>x = \sqrt{u}</m> , so that
              </intertext>
              <mrow>\int x^2\sqrt{x^3+1}\dx{x}\amp{}=
              \frac12\int\frac{u\sqrt{u^{3/2}}}{\sqrt{u}}\dx{u}</mrow>
              <mrow>\amp =
              \frac12 \int\sqrt{u}\sqrt{u^{3/2}+1}\dx{u}</mrow>
              <mrow>\amp
              =\frac12\int\sqrt{u^{5/2}+u}\dx{u}.</mrow>
            </md>
          </p>
          <p>
            This is all correct, but leads to an integral far worse than the
            original, But <mdash/> and this is the point of this example
            <mdash/> we have no way of seeing that this particular
            substitution will not be helpful until after we<rsq/>ve done the
            computations above.
          </p>
          <p>
            The lessons here are (1) Be patient with yourself, because this is hard, and (2)
            Don<rsq/>t give up, because this is hard.
          </p>
        </task>
        <task>
          <title>A Helpful Substitution</title>
          <p>
            But notice that <m>x^2</m> is almost the derivative of <m>x^3 +
            1</m>. So let's make <m>y = x^3 + 1</m> instead. Thus
            <m>\dx{y} = 3x^2 \dx{x}</m>. Will that extra  factor of <m>3</m>
            be a problem for us? Let<rsq/>s see.
          </p>
          <p>
            Making the substitution we have
            <md>
              <mrow>\int x^2\sqrt{x^3+1}\dx{x}\amp =\int
              x^2\sqrt{y}\left(\frac{\dx{y}}{3x^2}\right)</mrow>
              <mrow>\amp =\frac13\int y^{1/2}\dx{y}</mrow>
              <mrow>\amp =\frac13\left(\frac{y^{3/2}}{3/2}\right)+c</mrow>
              <mrow>\amp =\frac29\left(x^3+1\right)^{3/2}+c</mrow>
            </md>
          </p>
        </task>
      </example>
      <p>
        So what's the method for making a  substitution?
        Unfortunately, there is none. Basically, you can try
        anything. If it works, great!  If it doesn't, don't do
        something incorrectly to try and force it. Try something
        else. Our Rule of Thumb will help, but there are no guarantees. This is
        what makes integration harder than differentiation, much as
        long division is harder than multiplication.
      </p>
      <p>
        The problem will not solve itself.  Try something!  As you practice,
        you will gain more experience.  Look for formulas, methods, and
        ideas  that you have seen before. Maybe they can be tweaked to
        address your problem. Maybe they can be applied directly. You
        won<rsq/>t know until you try.
      </p>
      <p>
        And Practice, Practice, Practice!
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <p>
      As a general rule the more integrals you know the better. This is
      because the integration techniques you will be learning do not allow
      you to compute an integral. They merely show you how to transform one
      integral into another. You saw this in <xref
      ref="EQUATIONBadTanInt1">equation</xref> when we transformed
      <me>\int\tan(x)\dx{x}</me> into
      <me>\int\frac{u}{1+u^2}\dx{u}</me> and in <xref
      ref="EXAMPLEIntTan"></xref> when we transformed
      <me>\int\tan(x)\dx{x}</me> into
      <me>-\int\frac{\dx{z}}{z}.</me> We did not compute these integrals, we
      merely transformed them. In <xref
      ref="EXAMPLEIntTan"></xref> we transformed <m>\int\tan(x)\dx{x} </m>
      into an integral that we knew from our work in differentiation, but
      this was information that we simply drew from our memory.
    </p>
    <p>
      For that reason it is best to simply know <mdash/> that is, to  have memorized
      <mdash/> as many integrals as you can. Each integral you know provides
      a target, something you can aim for as you try to transform  a new
      integral into one you know.
    </p>
    <!-- <problem  xml:id="IntSECCSC"> -->
    <!--   <title>The Integrals of the Secant and Cosecant Functions</title> -->
    <!--   <introduction> -->
    <!--     <p> -->
    <!--       At this point we have know the integrals of the <m>\sin(x) </m>, -->
    <!--       <m>\cos(x) </m>, <m>\tan(x) </m>, and <m>\cot(x) </m>. The first two -->
    <!--       were immediate consequences of the differentiation rules, but the -->
    <!--       <m>\tan(x) </m>, and <m>\cot(x) </m> were harder.  -->
    <!--     </p> -->
    <!--   </introduction> -->
    <!--   <task> -->
    <!--     <statement> -->
    <!--       <p> -->
    <!--         Compute <m>\int\sec(x)\dx{x} </m> using the following trick: -->
    <!--         <me>\int\sec(x)\dx{x} = \int\sec(x)\underbrace{\frac{\tan (x)+\sec (x)}{\tan -->
    <!--         (x)+\sec (x)}}_{=1}\dx{x}.</me> -->
    <!--       </p> -->
    <!--       <p> -->
    <!--         Differentiate your solution to verify that its derivative is -->
    <!--         <m>\sec(x) </m>. -->
    <!--       </p> -->
    <!--     </statement> -->
    <!--     <hint> -->
    <!--       <p> -->
    <!--         Do you recognize a substitution that can be used? If so, use it. If -->
    <!--         not, try something. -->
    <!--       </p> -->
    <!--     </hint> -->
    <!--   </task> -->
    <!--   <task> -->
    <!--     <statement> -->
    <!--       <p> -->
    <!--         Use a similar trick to compute <m>\int \csc(x) \dx{x} </m>. -->
    <!--       </p> -->
    <!--     </statement> -->
    <!--   </task> -->

    <!-- </problem> -->

    <exercise xml:id="PROBLEMIntSECCSC">
      <title>The Integrals of the Secant and Cosecant Functions</title>
      <introduction>
        <p>
          At this point we have know the integrals of the <m>\sin(x) </m>,
          <m>\cos(x) </m>, <m>\tan(x) </m>, and <m>\cot(x) </m>. The first two
          were immediate consequences of the differentiation rules, but the
          <m>\tan(x) </m>, and <m>\cot(x) </m> were harder.
        </p>
      </introduction>
      <task xml:id="PROBLEMIntSECCSCA">
        <statement>
          <p>
            Confirm the identity:
            <m>\sec(x) =\frac{\cos(x) }{1-\sin^2(x) }. </m>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </task>
      <task xml:id="PROBLEMIntSECCSCB">
        <statement>
          <p>
            Confirm the identity: <m>\frac{1}{1-\sin^2(x) }=
            \frac12{\left[\frac{1}{1+\sin(x) } + \frac{1}{1-\sin(x) }\right] }</m>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Use the observations in <xref ref="PROBLEMIntSECCSCA">Problem</xref> and
            <xref ref="PROBLEMIntSECCSCB">Problem</xref> and a well chosen substitution
            to show that

            <me>\int\sec(x)\dx{x} = \ln \abs{\sec(x) + \tan(x)} </me>
          </p>
          <aside>
            <title>Comment:</title>
            <p>
              We have absolute value bars around the expression <m>\sec(x)+\tan(x)
              </m> to ensure that we are not trying to take the logarithm of a
              negative number. These will not appear obviously in any of the  computations
              you need to do. Just tack them on at the end, like we did.
            </p>
          </aside>
        </statement>
      </task>

      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Compute <m>\int \csc(x) \dx{x} </m> similarly.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </task>

    </exercise>

    <paragraphs xml:id="DIGRESSIONIntPolySecTan">
      <title>DIGRESSION: The Integral of an Arbitrary Polynomial
      in
      <m>\sec(x) </m> and <m>\tan{x} </m></title>
      <p>
        In
        many Calculus textbooks  the integral of the secant function is
        developed using the following<fn>This digression is based on the paper
        <pubtitle>
          <url href="https://www.jstor.org/stable/2589620" visual="https://www.jstor.org/stable/2589620">Integrating Polynomials in Secant and Tangent</url>
          </pubtitle>, by
          Jonathan P. McCammond,
          The American Mathematical Monthly, Nov.,
          1999, Vol. 106, No. 9</fn> trick:

          <md>
            <mrow>\int\sec(x)\dx{x} \amp{}= \int\sec(x)\underbrace{\frac{\tan (x)+\sec (x)}{\tan
            (x)+\sec (x)}}_{=1}\dx{x}.
            </mrow>
            <intertext>Now let <m>u=\tan(x)+\sec(x) </m> so that <m>\dx{u}
            =\sec(x)\tan(x)+\sec^2(x) </m> so that</intertext>
            <mrow>\amp{}=\int\frac1u\dx{u}</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp{}=\ln\abs{u}+c</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp{}=\ln\abs{\sec(x)+\tan(x)} +c</mrow>
          </md>
      </p>
      <p>
        Clearly whoever first computed the value of this integral found it by
        some other means (possibly by guessing) and then realized that
        multiplying by <m>\frac{\tan (x)+\sec (x)}{\tan(x)+\sec (x)}</m> and
        using the substitution <m>u=\tan(x)+\sec(x) </m> would suffice, even
        if it is not very illuminative.
      </p>
      <p>
        As an means of computing the integral this is fine. But as a teaching
        example it leaves a lot to be desired. In particular, there is no
        discernible reason for multiplying the integrand by one in this
        particular form. It is clearly a trick that was devised after the
        value of the integral had already been determined.
      </p>
      <aside>
        <title>Comment</title>
        <p>
          An old joke says that a <q>technique</q> is a <q>trick</q> that you
          use more than once.
        </p>
      </aside>
      <p>
        We have called this a trick, but we can turn it into a technique by
        finding the underlying structure of the problem. We begin by defining:

        <mdn>
          <mrow xml:id="EQUATIONPolySecTanUSubA">u\amp{}=\sec(x)+\tan(x)</mrow>
          <mrow xml:id="EQUATIONPolySecTanUSubB">v\amp{}=\sec(x)-\tan(x)</mrow>
        </mdn>

        from which we see that

        <mdn>
          <mrow xml:id="EQUATIONSecTanInvSubA">\sec(x) \amp{}=\frac12 (u+v)</mrow>
          <mrow xml:id="EQUATIONSecTanInvSubB">\tan(x) \amp{}=\frac12 (u-v).</mrow>
        </mdn>
      </p>
      <problem>
        <task>
          <statement>
            <p>
              Show that <men xml:id="EQUATIONSecTanEq1">uv=1.</men>
            </p>
          </statement>
        </task>
        <task>
          <statement>
            <p>
              Show that <men xml:id="EQUATIONSetTanDifferentials">\sec(x)\dx{x} = \frac1u \dx{u} = - \frac1v \dx{v}. </men>
            </p>
          </statement>
        </task>

      </problem>

      <example xml:id="EXAMPLEIntPolySecTan">
        <task xml:id="PROBLEMIntPolySecTanA">
          <statement>
            <p>
              For our first example we will compute 
              <md>
                <mrow>
                  \int\sec^3(x)\dx{x} \amp{}= \int \sec^2(x)\sec{x}\dx{x} 
                </mrow>
              </md>
              From <xref ref="EQUATIONSecTanInvSubA">equation</xref> we have
              <md>
                <mrow>
                  \int\sec^3(x)\dx{x}\amp{}=\frac14\int(u+v)^2\sec(x)\dx{x}
                </mrow>
                <mrow>
                  \amp{}=\frac14\int(u^2+2uv+v^2)\sec(x)\dx{x}
                </mrow>
              </md>
              and from <xref ref="EQUATIONSecTanEq1">equation</xref> we have
              <md>
                <mrow>
                  \int\sec^3(x)\dx{x}\amp{}=\frac14\int(u^2+2+v^2))\sec(x)\dx{x}
                </mrow>
                <mrow>
                  =\amp{}\frac14\int u^2\left(\frac{1}{u}\dx{u}\right) -\frac14
                  \int v^2\left(\frac{1}{v}\dx{v}\right)+\frac12\int\sec(x)\dx{x}
                </mrow>
                <mrow>
                  =\amp{}\frac18\left(u^2-v^2\right)+\frac12\int\sec(x)\dx{x}
                </mrow>
                <mrow>
                  =\amp{}\frac18\left[\sec(x)+\tan(x)\right]^2
                  <!-- </mrow> -->
                  <!-- <mrow> -->
                  <!--   \amp{} -->-\frac18\left[\sec(x)-\tan(x)\right]^2
                  <!-- </mrow> -->
                  <!-- <mrow> -->
                  <!--   \amp{} -->+\frac12\abs{\sec(x)+\tan(x)}+c
                </mrow>
                <mrow>
                  =\amp{}\frac18\left[\sec^2(x)+2\sec(x)\tan(x)
                  +\tan^2(x)\right]
                </mrow>              
                <mrow>
                  \amp{}-\frac18\left[\sec^2(x)-2\sec(x)\tan(x) +\tan^2(x)\right]
                </mrow>
                <mrow>
                  \amp{}+\frac12\abs{\sec(x)+\tan(x)}+c.
                </mrow>                  
              </md>
              So, finally,
              <me>
                \int\sec^3(x)\dx{x}=\frac12\left(\sec(x)\tan(x)+\abs{\sec(x)+\tan(x)}\right)+c.
              </me>
            </p>
          </statement>
        </task>

        <!-- <task  xml:id="PROBLEMEXAMPLEIntPolySecTanA"> -->
        <!-- <statement> -->
        <!-- <p> -->
        <!-- For our first example we will compute <m>\int\sec(x)\dx{x} </m> again. -->
        <!-- <me> -->
        <!-- \int\sec(x)\dx{x}=\int\frac1u\dx{u} = \ln\abs{u}+c=\ln\abs{\sec{x}+\tan{x}}+c -->
        <!-- </me> -->
        <!-- </p> -->
        <!-- </statement> -->
        <!-- </task> -->
        <!-- <task xml:id="PROBLEMEXAMPLEIntPolySecTanB"> -->
        <!-- <p> -->
        <!-- Since <m>\dx{\left(\sec(x)\right)}=\tan(x)\sec(x) -->
        <!--   </m> and <m>\dx{\left( -->
        <!-- \tan(x)\right)} =\sec^2(x) </m>   we know that -->
        <!-- <m>\int\sec^2(x)\dx{x} = \tan(x)+c</m> and -->
        <!-- <m>\int\tan(x)\sec(x)\dx{x} -->
        <!-- </m>. For our second example we will -->
        <!-- re-derive these results. -->

        <!-- <ol marker="i"> -->
        <!-- <li> -->

        <!-- <md> -->
        <!-- <mrow>\int\tan(x)\sec(x)\dx{x} \amp{}=\frac12 \int -->
        <!-- (u-v)\sec(x)\dx{x} </mrow> -->
        <!-- <mrow>\amp{}=\frac12\int u\left(\frac{1}{u}\dx{u}\right) + \frac12 -->
        <!-- \int v\left(\frac{1}{v}\dx{v}\right)</mrow> -->
        <!-- <mrow>\amp{}=\frac12(u+v)+c</mrow> -->
        <!-- <mrow>\amp{}=\sec(x)+c</mrow> -->
        <!-- </md> -->

        <!-- </li> -->
        <!-- <li> -->
        <!-- <p> -->
        <!-- <md> -->
        <!-- <mrow>\int\sec^2(x) \dx{x} \amp{}= \int \sec(x)\sec(x)\dx{x}{}</mrow> -->
        <!-- <mrow>\amp{}=\frac12\int(u+v)\sec(x)\dx{x}</mrow> -->
        <!-- <mrow>\amp{}=\frac12\left[\int u\sec(x)\dx{x} + \int v\sec(x)\dx{x}\right]</mrow> -->
        <!-- <mrow> -->
        <!-- \amp{}=\frac12\left[\int u\left(\frac{1}{u}\dx{u}\right) - \int v\left(-\frac{1}{v}\dx{v}\right)\right] -->
        <!-- </mrow> -->
        <!-- <mrow> -->
        <!-- \amp{}=\frac12\left(\int\dx{u} - \int\dx{v}\right) -->
        <!-- </mrow> -->
        <!-- <mrow> -->
        <!-- \amp{}=\frac12\left(u-v\right)+c -->
        <!-- </mrow> -->
        <!-- <mrow> -->
        <!-- \amp{}= \frac12\left[\sec(x)+\tan(x)- -->
        <!-- \left(\sec(x)-\tan(x)\right)\right] +c -->
        <!-- </mrow> -->
        <!-- <mrow> \amp{}= \tan(x)+c</mrow> -->
        <!-- </md> -->

        <!-- </p> -->
        <!-- </li> -->
        <!-- <li> -->

        <!-- <md> -->
        <!-- <mrow>\int\sec^2(x)\tan(x)\dx{x} \amp{}= \int -->
        <!-- \sec(x)\tan(x)\left(\sec{x}\dx{x}\right) </mrow> -->
        <!-- <mrow>\amp{}=\frac14\int(u+v)(u-v)\sec(x)\dx{x}</mrow> -->
        <!-- <mrow>\amp{}=\frac14\int u^2\left(\frac1u\dx{u}\right) + \frac14\int -->
        <!-- v^2\left(\frac1v\dx{v}\right)</mrow> -->
        <!-- <mrow>\amp{}=\frac18\left(u^2 + v^2\right) +c</mrow> -->
        <!-- <mrow> -->
        <!-- \amp{}=\frac18\left[\sec^2(x) +2\sec(x)\tan(x) +\tan^2(x) -->
        <!-- -\left(\sec^2(x) + 2\sec(x)\tan(x) +\tan^2(x)\right)\right]+c -->
        <!-- </mrow> -->
        <!-- <mrow>\amp{}=\frac14\left(\sec^2(x)+\tan^2(x)\right)+c</mrow> -->
        <!-- </md> -->



        <!-- </li> -->
        <!-- </ol> -->
        <!-- </p> -->
        <!-- </task> -->

      </example>
      <p>
        In fact, in the paper cited above, McCammond shows that if
        <m>P(s,t)</m> is any polynomial in two variables then

        <me>\int P\left(\sec(x), \tan(x)\right)\dx{x}</me>

        can be evaluated using the substitutions in equations <xref
        ref="EQUATIONPolySecTanUSubA"></xref> and <xref
        ref="EQUATIONPolySecTanUSubB"></xref>, their properties in equations
        <xref ref="EQUATIONSecTanInvSubA"></xref> and <xref ref=",
        EQUATIONSecTanInvSubB"></xref> above, and the judicious use of the
        Pythagorean trigonometric identity 
        <men xml:id="EQUATIONPythSecTan">\tan^2(x)+1=\sec^2(x).</men>
      </p>

      <exercise  xml:id="PROBLEMPolySecTan">
        <introduction>
          <p>
            <idx><h>Problme</h></idx>

            Evaluate the integrals and differentiate your  solution to confirm
            that it is  correct.
          </p>
        </introduction>
        <task>
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>\int \sec^5(x) \dx{x} </m>
            </p>
          </statement>
        </task>
        <task>
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>\int \tan^3(x) \dx{x} </m>
            </p>
          </statement>
        </task>
        <task>
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>\int \sec^4(x)\tan(x) \dx{x} </m>
            </p>
          </statement>
        </task>
        <task>
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>\int \sec^3(x)\tan^5(x) \dx{x} </m>
            </p>
          </statement>
        </task>
      </exercise>
      <p>
        These substitutions are clever and they give us an elegant solution
        but we do not necessarily want an elegant solution. In most cases
        where the evaluation of an integral is required we<rsq/>ll just want
        obtain a
        solution in the most efficient manner possible.
      </p>

      <exercise xml:id="PROBLEMPolySecTanByTrigSub">
        <introduction>
          <p>
            <idx><h>Problem</h></idx>

            Evaluate the following integrals and differentiate your  solution to confirm
            that it is  correct. The method we<rsq/>ve described in this
            digression will work, but is not the necessarily always the most efficient
            method available.
          </p>
        </introduction>
        <task>
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>\int \sec^2(x)+\sec(x)\tan(x)\dx{x} </m>
            </p>
          </statement>
        </task>
        <task>
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>\int \sec^3(x)\tan(x)+\tan^3(x)\sec(x)\dx{x} </m>
            </p>
          </statement>
        </task>
        <task>
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>\int \left(1+\sec(x)+\sec^2(x)+\sec^3(x)+\sec^4(x) \right)\tan(x)
              \dx{{x}  }</m>
            </p>
          </statement>
        </task>
        <task>
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>\int \left(1+\tan(x)+\tan^2(x)+\tan^3(x)+\tan^4(x) \right)\sec(x)
              \dx{{x}  }</m>
            </p>
          </statement>
        </task>

      </exercise>


      <exercise xml:id="PROBLEMPolyCscCot">
        <introduction>
          <p>
            <idx><h>Problem</h></idx>


            Evaluate the following integrals and differentiate your  solution to confirm
            that it is  correct. The method we<rsq/>ve described in this
            digression will work, but is not the necessarily always the most efficient
            method available.
            (You will need to find substitutions analogous to those we developed
            above.)
          </p>
        </introduction>
        <task>
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>\int \csc^2(x)+\csc(x)\cot(x)\dx{x} </m>
            </p>
          </statement>
        </task>
        <task>
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>\int \csc^3(x)\cot(x)+\cot^3(x)\csc(x)\dx{x} </m>
            </p>
          </statement>
        </task>
        <task>
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>\int \left(1+\csc(x)+\csc^2(x)+\csc^3(x)+\csc^4(x) \right)\cot(x)
              \dx{{x}  }</m>
            </p>
          </statement>
        </task>
        <task>
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>\int \left(1+\cot(x)+\cot^2(x)+\cot^3(x)+\cot^4(x) \right)\csc(x)
              \dx{{x}  }</m>
            </p>
          </statement>
        </task>

      </exercise>


      <p><alert>END OF DIGRESSION</alert></p>
    </paragraphs>
  </section>
</chapter>
